  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms in the LLVM project (repo: sg-evals/llvm-project--a8f3c97d):\n\n1. **StackProtector pass** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp`): This is the primary LLVM pass that inserts stack protector checks against buffer overflow attacks. The class `StackProtector` (a `FunctionPass`) and the static function `InsertStackProtectors` implement the core logic: in the prologue, a stack guard value is written to the stack frame; in the epilogue, the stored value is compared against the original and `__stack_chk_fail` is called if they differ. The pass is registered via `INITIALIZE_PASS_BEGIN(StackProtector, ...)` with description 'Insert stack protectors'.\n\n2. **SafeStack pass** (`llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp`): Implements the SafeStack instrumentation pass (`SafeStackPass`) that separates safe and unsafe stack allocations. Variables that cannot be proven safe (e.g., those whose address is taken or used in unsafe ways) are moved to a separate 'unsafe stack', while safe variables remain on the regular stack. This prevents stack-based buffer overflows from corrupting return addresses and other sensitive data. The companion file `llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.cpp` handles the layout of the unsafe stack frame.\n\n3. **Stack protection pass interface header** (`llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h`): Declares the `StackProtector` (legacy FunctionPass) and `StackProtectorPass` (new pass manager) classes. Also, `llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/SafeStack.h` declares `SafeStackPass`.\n\n4. **`__stack_chk_fail` runtime implementation** (`libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp`): Provides the `__stack_chk_fail()` function that is called at runtime when a stack smashing attack is detected (i.e., when the stack canary value has been corrupted). It writes 'stack smashing detected' to stderr and terminates the program. Note: this is in the LLVM libc implementation; the task asked to look under `compiler-rt/lib/builtins/` but the actual implementation resides in `libc/src/compiler/generic/`.\n\n5. **Memory safety instrumentation for stack frames** (`llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/AddressSanitizer.cpp`): Implements AddressSanitizer (ASan) instrumentation including the `FunctionStackPoisoner` class which instruments stack frames to detect stack-based buffer overflows, use-after-return, and use-after-scope bugs. It poisons/unpoisons shadow memory around stack allocations and uses `AsanStackMallocFunc`/`AsanStackFreeFunc` for dynamic stack frame management. The `HWAddressSanitizer.cpp` in the same directory also provides `instrumentStack` for hardware-assisted memory tagging of stack frames."
